&quot;The recent rumours about MB being nerfed on Test got me thinking about a possible solution to the whole debacle.&quot;<br>
<br>
What debacle? You mean that melees have their panties in a wad because something of even minor significance was accomplished without them and their blessed trinity. Funny, I seem to recall about 59 levels of melees getting things done without me.<br>
<br>
Quote:<br>
&quot;It's simple. If 50%(or some other appropriate percentage) or more of a mob's life is taken by manaburn(and this counts all manaburns) then it leaves no corpse and gives no exp.&quot;<br>
<br>
Thanks, but I already have disintegrate and would prefer not to have 2 spells I virtually never use let alone one that will require 23 earned aa points.<br>
<br>
Quote:<br>
&quot;Small guilds with one or two manaburn enabled wizards would still be able to help out in Kunark encounter. Wait until that dragon hits 49%, and burn away.&quot;<br>
<br>
I assume this refers to the common argument that manaburn has trivialized a small handful of encounters. So, making them half as trivial fixes the &quot;problem?&quot; Incidentally, I would like to point out that the draught and jyl's lines have done far more to trivialize my encounters with fire beetles, but I digress..<br>
<br>
Quote:<br>
&quot;It would still be useful to take down normal mobs immediately, when you absolutely positively have to stop that CHing cleric mob.&quot;<br>
<br>
If you're relying on a skill useable only once every 2 hours to interrupt CH'ing mobs then your problems go far beyond whatever encounters manaburn may or may not have trivialized.<br>
<br>
Quote:<br>
&quot;The only thing that would change is that 'Team Manaburn' would be unable to farm dragons for loot.&quot;<br>
<br>
Oh good, then Team Holy Trinity can get back to farming it with their 6 man teams. <br>
<br>
Quote:<br>
&quot;Perhaps in compensation, have manaburn scale slightly based on a mob's total HP. Nothing astronomical, maybe 25% higher or so on mobs with hundreds of thousands of hitpoints.&quot;<br>
<br>
Imho, this is the first sensible suggestion. Compare the damage a 60 wizard can do on a full bar vs. the damage done with manaburn. If anything, they should up the damage on manaburn to bring it up to 3:1 or so (someone made a post about this recently showing a pic of a 13k non-crit mb so maybe it already does hit 3:1 or better /shrug).<br>
<br>
Quite honestly, when all these people get up in arms about the &quot;fearsome power&quot; of manaburn they seem to forget some really important facts.<br>
<br>
1. 23 AA points minimum to get it.<br>
2. 2.5 Hour Re-Use delay.<br>
3. 100% mana drain upon use.<br>
4. Set damage limit based on available mana.<br>
5. 6 second casting time.<br>
<br>
Manaburn falls right in line with what wizards have always excelled at in the past -- Raiding. It is a raid tool.<br>
<br>
All these people whining and up in arms over &quot;ks'ing wizzies&quot; need to seriously reconsider their positions before they whine themselves right out of a nice tool that works for THEIR benefit. Additionally, has anyone ever noticed how there has never been a single peep made about Dragon or Giant's Banes? They achieve a damage ratio and total that far exceeds that of manaburn.<br>
<br>
Tal<br>
